<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910522-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>910522-0037.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Unisys Corp.:   Computer Firm to Unveil   A `Fault-Tolerant' System</HL><DATE>05/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   UIS</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><RE>PENNSYLVANIA (PA)</RE><LP>   Unisys Corp. will unveil today a &quot;fault-tolerant&quot; computersystem that it said would help ensure several years ofhealthy demand for its 2200 family of mainframe computers.   Fault-tolerant systems, designed to keep working even ifseveral parts fail, are increasingly used by airlines, banksand other firms that need extremely reliable computers. Thenew Unisys scheme hooks together as many as four 2200mainframes so they can all gain access to records from thesame database; individual machines can break down, or beserviced, without affecting the system.</LP><TEXT>   Unisys said its product, dubbed Gladiator, will be able toprocess as many as 3,000 transactions every second using thecompany's current top-of-the-line 2200 model. Performancewill increase tenfold over the next few years, the firmadded, through a combination of technical tweaks and theintroduction of new 2200 models this fall.   Unisys said its new product will cost between $3 millionand $50 million and will be available starting in the fourthquarter.</TEXT></DOC>